<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264358" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/ian-frazier-the-snakes-that-ate-florida-reporting-essays-and-criticism/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Ian Frazier, The Snakes That Ate Florida- Reporting, Essays, and Criticism" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism-683x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-264358" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism-200x300.jpg" alt="Ian Frazier, The Snakes That Ate Florida: Reporting, Essays, and Criticism" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ian-Frazier-The-Snakes-That-Ate-Florida-Reporting-Essays-and-Criticism.jpg 1000w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Ian Frazier, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780374603106" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Snakes That Ate Florida</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(FSG)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A rich smorgasbord from a master of his form.&#8221;<br />
<em>–Publishers Weekly</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264866" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-old-fire/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg.jpg" data-orig-size="263,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="the old fire" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-264866" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg-197x300.jpg" alt="the old fire" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/the-old-fire-9781668212219_lg.jpg 263w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Elisa Shua Dusapin, trans. by Aneesa Abbas Higgins, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781668212219" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Old Fire</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Summit)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A bewitching meditation on tenderness and violence, intimacy and estrangement.&#8221;<br />
<em>–</em>Tess Gunty</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="265150" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/karl-ove-knausgaard-niall-williams-daniyal-mueenuddin-and-more-21-new-books-out-today/hitch/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch.jpg" data-orig-size="800,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Hitch, Sara Levine" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch-683x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-265150" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch-200x300.jpg" alt="The Hitch, Sara Levine" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/hitch.jpg 800w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sara Levine, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780802165923" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Hitch</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Roxane Gay Books)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;One of the most wildly comedic and unhinged novels I have ever encountered, while at the same time also being deeply relatable and strangely emotionally accurate.&#8221;<br />
<em>–</em>Elizabeth Gilbert</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="265151" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/karl-ove-knausgaard-niall-williams-daniyal-mueenuddin-and-more-21-new-books-out-today/attachment/9781593768034/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/9781593768034.jpeg" data-orig-size="300,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Plastic, Matthew RIce" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/9781593768034-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/9781593768034.jpeg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-265151" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/9781593768034-200x300.jpeg" alt="Plastic, Matthew RIce" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/9781593768034-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/9781593768034-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/9781593768034-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/9781593768034.jpeg 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Matthew Rice, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781593768034" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Plastic: A Poem</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(Soft Skull)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;A book-length poem exploring the life of the industrial worker turned poet.&#8221;<br />
<em>–</em>From the publisher</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="265152" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/karl-ove-knausgaard-niall-williams-daniyal-mueenuddin-and-more-21-new-books-out-today/attachment/233411630/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/233411630.jpg" data-orig-size="331,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jean, Madeleine Dunnigan" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/233411630-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/233411630.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-265152" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/233411630-199x300.jpg" alt="Jean, Madeleine Dunnigan" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/233411630-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/233411630-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/233411630-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/233411630.jpg 331w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Madeleine Dunnigan, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781324105640" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Jean</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>(W. W. Norton)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">&#8220;It&#8217;s luscious and at the same time spiky, graceful and explosive, magical and brutal.&#8221;<br />
<em>–</em>Lillian Fishman</p>
